NSA case highlights complete lack of intelligence debate
How to explain the contradictory attitude of the French government, which on the one hand is publicly offended by summoning the US ambassador on October 21, and on the other prohibits the overflight of the territory by the Bolivian presidential plane, on the basis of the rumor of the presence on board of Edward Snowden?
In my opinion, there are two levels of response from the French government.
When Fran√ßois Hollande telephones Barack Obama or when Foreign Minister Laurent Fabius summons the US ambassador, they react to a real discovery, which is that of the extent of American surveillance of all communications in France.
Is it not surprising to read in the columns of Le Monde a few weeks apart on the one hand the reproduction of American diplomatic correspondence and on the other hand a condemnation of the wiretapping of the Quai d'Orsay by the NSA?
Wouldn't there be a vague hypocrisy on your part?
The journalistic approach is not a moral position, but the search for the interest and relevance of information that allows each citizen to form an opinion.
When WikiLeaks lifts the veil on the analysis by American diplomacy of political or other issues around the world, we consider that, in view of American power, this constitutes an important insight.
When we describe American interception systems against French diplomacy in the United States, it is in no way to be indignant about this practice, it is to describe the world as it is.
Did the France benefit from information provided by the NSA regarding terrorist operations targeting our interests?
Can we deprive ourselves of American collaboration?
The implementation for roughly ten years of very powerful technological interception tools by the United States, but also by the France, has officially been justified by the fight against terrorism.
Moreover, in this area, the France and the United States in particular have set up procedures for cooperation and exchange of information on an almost daily basis and which are described on both sides as essential.
For example, the presence of Mohammed Merah in the tribal areas in Miranshah was reported to the French thanks to the NSA's resources.
The France may be led, for example, to transmit entire blocks of data on the Sahel region to the American services, and, in return - as has already been quickly said - the Americans can give information to the French on other regions of the world.
So the fundamental question behind this NSA affair is not so much the ability or the right of countries to equip themselves with interception tools, but the question of the total absence of prior debate, particularly in parliaments, on the justification of such systems, the perimeter that should be theirs, and, ultimately,  the question of infringements of freedoms.
What is the real risk for the United States? a degradation of their image?
No matter how much we denounce them, I do not see how they can be punished.
The risk to Americans may be twofold.
The first is when their allies - and this has been the case recently - learn that their leaders, sometimes at the highest level of their state, have been monitored.
This is the case of Brazil and Germany, two countries where diplomatic relations with the United States have become strained.
Another effect may be more economical: more and more European or South American companies are reluctant, in the light of the revelations, to entrust their confidential data to American service providers subject to American laws, and therefore to the control of the NSA.
Finally, the vast movement of revelations initiated by media around the world, which contributes to triggering a debate on the surveillance practices of the intelligence services hitherto almost non-existent, could push legislators, including American ones, to reconsider the powers they have given to their intelligence services.
Barack Obama receives the Iraqi Prime Minister, in the midst of an outbreak of violence
The US president was to receive Friday, November 1, 2013 Iraqi Prime Minister Nouri Al Maliki, seeking help from the United States to fight the strongest wave of violence in five years.
Iraq experienced in October its deadliest month in five and a half years, according to figures published Friday, November 1 by the Iraqi authorities.
964 people died in the violence in October, including 855 civilians, 65 police and 44 soldiers, and 1,600 people were injured.
The UN gives an even higher toll with 979 dead and 1,902 wounded.
The violence has become increasingly deadly despite heightened security measures and large-scale military operations launched months ago by the Shia-dominated government of Nuri al-Maliki.
The total death toll in October was the highest since April 2008, when 1,073 people were killed.
About two years after the withdrawal of US troops, the level of violence raises fears of a new conflagration as neighboring Syria is in the grip of a civil war.
Bombs hit markets, mosques, weddings and funerals.
Men are shot dead in the street or even in their homes, and security forces are also the target of frequent attacks.
The growing discontent of the Sunni minority, in power under Saddam Hussein, who complain of being politically marginalized and the target of unjust arrests, has contributed to this outbreak of violence.
On Friday, fresh violence killed four people in northern Iraq, a day after at least 26 people were killed in a series of bombings, including the explosion of five car bombs north of Baghdad.
Much of the violence has been blamed on the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL), an Al-Qaeda (Sunni extremist) affiliate also involved in Syria's civil war.
Nouri Al Maliki wants a "world war" against al-Qaeda.
The violence is at the center of talks in the United States by Prime Minister Nouri Al Maliki, who will be received Friday by President Barack Obama, two years after their previous meeting, on December 12, 2011.
At the time, the US president, elected on a promise to end military involvement in that country, painted an optimistic picture of the situation.
Since his arrival Wednesday in Washington, Nouri Al Maliki has multiplied meetings with the executive, and elected members of Congress.
On Thursday, he called for the international community to wage a "third world war" against al-Qaeda.
The principle of increased security assistance to Iraq is supported by influential Republican and Democratic senators.
But they also criticized Nuri al-Maliki, a Shiite, attributing to him the partial responsibility for the resumption of violence by his "sectarian and authoritarian politics".
