FAA: Air passengers can now use gadgets on board planes (but not make a call with their cell phone)
Airline passengers will be able to use their door-to-door electronics to read, work, play games, watch movies and listen to music ‚Äî but not talk on their cell phones ‚Äî under the long-awaited new guidelines released Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration.
But passengers shouldn't expect immediate changes.
The speed with which the change will be implemented will vary from airline to airline, FAA Administrator Michael Huerta said at a news conference.
Airlines will have to prove to the FAA that their planes meet the new guidelines and that they have updated crew training manuals and aircraft storage rules to be compliant.
The FAA said it has already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of electronic devices on their planes.
Delta and JetBlue are among the companies that have already submitted plans.
"Depending on the plan, we may approve expanded use of electronic devices very soon," the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers must turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the aircraft doors are closed.
They are not supposed to turn them back on until the plane reaches an altitude of 10,000 feet and the captain gives the green light.
Passengers are supposed to turn off their devices when the plane descends before landing and not turn them back on until the plane has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose planes are properly protected from electronic interference will be able to allow passengers to use their devices during takeoffs, landings and taxiing, the FAA said.
Most of the new airliners and other planes that have been modified so that passengers can use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes, should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Association of Professional Flight Attendants, said she was pleased with the changes.
"Once the new policy is safely implemented ‚Äî and we will be working closely with carriers to do that ‚Äî it will benefit everyone," Glading said in a statement.
We are frankly tired of feeling like "room supervisors" when it comes to this issue.
But it will still be forbidden to connect to the internet to surf, exchange emails and text messages or download data below 10,000 feet, the agency said.
Passengers will have to put their smartphones, tablets and other devices in airplane mode.
So still no Words With Friends, the Scrabble-style online game that actor Alec Baldwin was playing on his smartphone in 2011 when he was loudly kicked out of an American Airlines plane after refusing to turn off his device while the plane was parked at the door.
And heavier devices like laptops will still need to be stowed away as they could hurt someone if they flew through the cabin.
Mobile phones on board will also continue to be banned.
Regulatory authority for cell phones rests with the Federal Communications Commission, not the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices during takeoff and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transportation safety expert on CBS News, said cell phones were still considered a risk.
"Cell phones are really a problem, not only because they could potentially create interference with navigational instruments, but because we know from the FCC that they could disrupt cell towers if used on board," Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to look into the problem recommended last month that the government allow wider use of personal electronic devices.
Pressure on the FAA has increased in recent years to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics such as Sen. Claire McCaskill, D-Mo., argue that there is no valid security reason for these bans.
Restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce as the use of devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies indicate that at least one-third of passengers forget to turn off their devices, or do so deliberately.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices in 1996 following reports of interference with navigation and communication instruments when passengers carried FM radios, the high-tech gadget of the time.
The new airliners rely much more on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed to withstand electronic interference and approved by the FAA.
Airlines have been allowing their passengers to use Wi-Fi at cruising altitudes for several years.
Aircraft modified to accommodate Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of airliners are expected to allow wider use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today's electronic devices generally emit radio transmissions of much lower power than previous generations of devices.
E-book readers, for example, emit only minimal transmissions when turning a page.
But transmissions are stronger when devices download or send data.
Amazon.com is among those pushing for a relaxation of restrictions on passengers' use of electronic devices.
In 2011, company executives loaded an airliner with Kindle e-book readers and flew it to see if there were any problems, but there were none.
This has left FAA advisory committee members with mixed feelings about whether or not the use of the aircraft poses a risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he believed interference from the aircraft was real, even if the risk was minimal.
Other members of the committee stated that there are only anecdotal reports from pilots that the aircraft can interfere with an aircraft's systems, and that most of them are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to instruct passengers to turn off their aircraft during instrument landings in low visibility conditions.
A travel industry group welcomed the changes, calling them common-sense arrangements for tech-equipped travelers.
"We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that an enjoyable passenger experience is not incompatible with safety," said Roger Dow, President and Director of the U.S. Travel Association.
The rules on the use of electronic devices on board remain in force in Australia for the time being.
Australian air passengers will have to continue to turn off their tablets and smartphones during take-off and landing despite the US move to relax regulations on electronic devices.
The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration has left the door open for U.S. carriers to change their procedures so passengers can read e-books, watch videos or play games on their devices during critical phases of flight as long as they are in "airplane" mode.
Passengers can already do this for most of the flight, but many people find it distressing not to be able to access their e-books during take-off and landing.
Australian carriers are reviewing the decision that requires U.S. carriers to do significant work to meet the requirements, but have indicated they have no immediate plans to change their procedures.
The Civil Aviation Safety Authority also said it was reviewing the announcement but stressed that restrictions on the use of electronic devices during critical phases of flight were still in place in Australia.
"CASA does not have specific regulations governing the use of electronic devices on airplanes," she said.
The issue is regulated by requiring aircraft operators to ensure the maintenance of safety at all times and passengers to follow the safety instructions given by crew members.
Virgin, which has previously spoken to CASA about plans to expand use of its in-flight entertainment system using Wi-Fi technology, was open to a change, but said it would follow the regulator.
"We would welcome a revision of CASA that would allow the use of electronic devices because we really believe it would improve the customer experience now that we have (the in-flight entertainment system using Wi-Fi technology) on our aircraft," a spokesperson said.
Qantas said it was currently complying with the current rules.
"In accordance with our current policy, electronic devices cannot be used during take-off and landing, and we have no immediate plans to change that," she said.
The FAA's decision applies to U.S. airlines.
However, we are still interested in regulatory developments that could benefit passengers, and we will closely review the FAA's decision and the reasons for it.
For U.S. carriers, the impact of the decision will vary from airline to airline and will depend on the age of their fleet.
Carriers will be required to demonstrate that their aircraft can tolerate radio interference from electronic devices, as well as review manuals, training materials, carry-on baggage programs and instructions provided to passengers.
"Once an airline has verified its fleet tolerance, it can allow passengers to use lightweight portable electronic devices, such as tablets, e-book readers, and smartphones at all altitudes," the FAA said.
In rare cases of low visibility, the crew will ask passengers to turn off their aircraft during landing.
The group also recommended that heavier aircraft be safely stowed under seats or in overhead compartments during take-off and landing.
