Privacy organizations confirm this enthusiasm for biometrics, but are concerned about it.
In 2011 and France alone, the National Commission for Informatics and Liberties authorized 774 systems for recognizing fingerprints, hand shape or venous network in companies, administrations, canteens...
"Everyone will soon be able to be identified, anywhere and anytime," said Justin Brookman, head of consumer privacy at the Center for Democracy and Technology (CDT) in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism in some and pessimism in others?
Biometrics will be based on new techniques, which will make it possible to provide new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most widely used biometric data are fingerprints, hand contour and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its constraints.
"For example, some people who work with concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are illegible," says Philippe Robin, technical director of identity at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection and verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand presupposes a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
This is both a security - we cannot capture this data without their knowledge - and a disadvantage: the procedure must sometimes be repeated and therefore takes time.
As a result, research has been conducted for twenty years on other approaches, such as facial or iris recognition (the colored part of the eye).
Thanks to the increase in the accuracy of sensors and the computing capacity of computers needed to analyze data, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has increased tenfold over the past five years, according to Cyrille Bataller, head of Accenture's R&D labs in Europe.
With our help, the UK and Holland have deployed automatic border posts using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
"Today, we're researching voice recognition or how to walk using sound sensors, but you need a quiet environment," says Sridhar Iyengar, director of security research at Intel Labs.
A unique and tamper-proof marker, DNA also raises hopes and concerns.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered as the ultimate biometric data," confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Foresight at the CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers the judicial police a suitcase costing 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples at the scene of a crime and in one hour.
The uses of biometrics fall into two groups: identification (recognizing one person among others) and authentication (ensuring that the person is who they say they are).
Until now, identification has concerned the issuance of identity documents: it is necessary to compare biometric elements (fingerprints, photo, iris) with the information that the State has on all citizens already registered.
This ensures that someone is not attempting to impersonate someone else.
This principle of comparison can have other applications.
NEC offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or shop.
"We retrieve the images from surveillance cameras and compare them to photos of celebrities that circulate freely on the Internet," says Dany Nassif, NEC France's business development manager for biometric identification solutions.
Another use is to take a picture of a person queuing up in a store, track its progress with facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
Authentication initially concerned physical access (borders, protected premises, canteens, etc.) or logical access (opening a computer).
More recently, attendance control has been added.
"A biometric time clock avoids the phenomenon of the buddy pointing for another," explains Cyrille Bataller, Accenture.
But, increasingly, authentication will also concern transactions, especially those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from certain ATMs by inserting your card and putting your hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the typing of the secret code.
A similar technique is being tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoul√™me by Natural Security in partnership with banks and supermarket chains: when paying in store with his credit card, the customer does not type his code, but enters his finger into a reader that scans the veins.
The experiment is scheduled to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French retailers.
Ways to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics appealing to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
"If, thanks to biometrics, a customer stays at the checkout thirty seconds less, it's appreciable," explains the manager of a supermarket.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you tailor-made options.
And, finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
"Fingerprints are stored on a first server; people's identities are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which crashes if you try to move it," says Philippe Robin of Thales.
