Scientists have just shed light on how a dog's tail movements are related to its mood.
Previous studies have found that happy dogs wag their tails more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs wag their tails more to the left.
But now scientists say dogs can detect these subtle differences and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: "Everyone knows that, in humans, the left and right side of the brain are involved in different ways in stimuli that arouse positive or negative emotions."
Here we tried to see what happened in other species.
He added that just as in humans, in dogs the right side of the brain is responsible for moving to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres play a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs respond to other dogs' disordered tail movements, the researchers tracked animals watching movies featuring other dogs.
They measured the animals' heart rate and analyzed their behavior.
It surely won't be long before we understand why their tails sometimes go to one side and sometimes to the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: "We showed dogs films featuring other dogs ‚Äì either a naturalistic version or a silhouette to avoid any other confounding factors ‚Äì and we were able to tamper with the movement of the tail and present it as going further left or right."
When the animals saw an expressionless dog wagging its tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog wagging its tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail deviating mostly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog wagging its tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think the dogs deliberately communicated with each other through these movements.
Rather, he thinks dogs know from experience what movements they should or shouldn't worry about.
He added: "If you repeatedly encounter other dogs and notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and the right side results in a less friendly attitude, you will react based on that experience."
The researchers say the findings could allow owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand their pets' emotions.
Canine behaviour expert John Bradshaw, a visiting professor at the University of Bristol's School of Veterinary Science, said this was not the first study to examine the importance of left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turned their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a cheerful dog.
And in another scientific study by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: "Dogs go more easily to a robot dog when its tail waggs to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious ‚Äì the opposite of what is in the Italian study."
He said the differences may be because the dogs that participated in the different studies did not entirely consider the animals in the movies or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study on how dogs react to real dogs could be helpful, he explained.
"While there are many elements found in different mammals that indicate that the two sides of the brain are being used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified ‚Äî and dogs are no exception," he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviors can be recorded, it surely won't be long before we understand why their tails sometimes move to one side and sometimes to the other.
