After hundreds of thousands of people received termination notices from their providers, Republicans have criticized the president in recent days by accusing him of misleading the American people.
Yesterday, Barack Obama adjusted his original promise.
"The vast majority of people with health insurance that is right for them can keep it," he said in a speech in Boston.
Speaking of what he calls "a buzz in the news" about terminations, President Obama urged Americans who receive these notices to seek new insurance in the market.
Most people will be able to get comprehensive and better adapted health plans for the same price, or even cheaper than expected.
"You will come out a winner," he said.
The Administration has announced that it should come as no surprise that the 5% of the population who purchase their own insurance are forced to switch plans because their coverage does not meet the new standards required under the Affordable Care Act.
"Let me speak directly to these Americans: You deserve better," Kathleen Sebelius said during her testimony before the Energy and Commerce Committee in Washington.
Sebelius, who oversees the implementation of the Affordable Care Act, said the October launch of the online marketplace had failed "miserably."
"I'm as frustrated and irritated as anyone else," she added.
I look forward to regaining your trust.
It was an exasperated Kathleen Sebelius who uttered this sentence, when she thought her microphone was cut off, while addressing an assistant sitting behind her during yesterday's Assembly session following a contentious exchange of views with Billy Long, Republican representative of Missouri, about whether she should adhere to Obamacare.
For more than three hours, Billy Long kept asking Sebelius why the "architect" of the Affordable Care Act hadn't voluntarily given up government-sponsored insurance to buy a plan through HealthCare.gov, which she now touts to millions of Americans.
The Coen brothers' tribute to folk
"Inside Llewyn Davis" by the Coen brothers, Grand Prix at the last Cannes Film Festival, is a nostalgic and funny film about the Greenwich village of 1961 and the folk music that was just beginning to resonate there, before the arrival of Bob Dylan.
Joel and Ethan Coen, whose filmography has just been the subject of a retrospective at the Cin√©math√®que fran√ßaise, won the Palme d'Or at Cannes in 1991 for Barton Fink.
Unable to hire Dylan or the trio Peter, Paul and Mary, Joel and Ethan Coen have set their sights on the rising star of American cinema, Oscar Isaac, 33, but also on the global pop star Justin Timberlake.
In this humorous film where music is a central character and songs performed live, Oscar Isaac proves to be an accomplished folk musician and singer, while Timberlake, his friend in the film, leaves pop for folk music with contagious jubilation.
As for Carey Mulligan, she left the rich trappings of Daisy Mulligan in "The Great Gatsby" for less shiny clothes, a soft voice when she sings, but the swear word spewed with a machine gun when she speaks.
"Inside Llewyn Davis" tells the week-long tribulations of a folk singer who can't break through and gets angry with the whole world.
He reluctantly accepts replacements at short notice in the studios.
Without housing, he makes the rounds of the sofas of his friends who still want to receive him.
An air of documentary
"His relationship with success is tortured, that's what interested us: a mixture of bad luck, a guy who is not there at the right time, who is not careerist but honest, with self-destructive behavior," Ethan Coen, crowned with his brother Joel of several Oscars and awards at Cannes, told the press.
If Llewyn Davis did not exist, the two filmmakers fans of folk music built their story on real personalities of the time like folk musician Dave Von Ronk.
The idea was to show the moment before the advent of Greenwich village, this neighborhood of New York destined to become "the epicenter of the rise of folk music that would generate international stars" as journalist Elijah Wald, friend of Van Ronk, writes.
The film then takes on the appearance of a documentary, from the dusty music label invaded by unsold 33T inhabited by an old unpayable secretary, to the musical choices of the studios of the time and the cafes where the singers performed.
The magic of the Coen brothers still operates by integrating a funny character who runs through the film constantly: a beautiful ginger cat with a cracking look, companion of fortune of Llewyn Davis.
Asked how he composed his character, actor and singer Justin Timberlake recalled having "grown up in Tennessee, bathed in blues and country".
"My first music lessons were given to me by my grandfather who taught me to play the guitar," he added.
For Justin Timberlake, if work is necessary to "be considered good", "chance can also launch someone's career", and "more and more today".
Like Llewyn Davis who refuses to compromise on his music, the pop star explains that in a career, "the most important thing is not to get stuck by everything that can prevent us from expressing ourselves".
