NSA spying: US 'went too far,' Kerry admits
The United States has sometimes gone "too far" in terms of espionage, acknowledged Secretary of State John Kerry, in this first admission of Washington in the midst of controversy with Europe on the massive collection of data by the National Security Agency (NSA).
After ten days of scandal, revelations and denials between the United States and its European allies, this is the first time that a US government official has explicitly admitted controversial practices in the NSA's interception of communications and data in Europe.
"In some cases, I concede to you, as the president did, some of these actions have gone too far and we will make sure that does not happen again in the future," John Kerry said at a conference in London that he participated from Washington Thursday, October 31 by video link.
In his retransmitted speech, in the presence of his British counterpart William Hague, the head of American diplomacy justified at length the practices of intelligence and information gathering by the necessary fight against terrorism and the prevention against possible attacks.
Invoking the attacks of September 11, 2001, the attacks in Madrid in March 2004 and those in London in July 2005, John Kerry assured that the American authorities had since foiled many plans for attacks, thanks to the interception of communications and the collection of information.
"We have in fact prevented planes from falling, buildings from exploding and people from being murdered, because we were able to be aware of these projects in advance," argued the head of American diplomacy.
And, John Kerry told the Europeans, "I assure you that in this process innocent people have not been deceived."
But we are trying to gather information.
"And yes, in some cases, it went too far inappropriately," admitted the secretary of state, who had already had to speak on this international scandal during a tour last week in Paris, London and Rome.
He assured Thursday night that President Obama was "committed to trying to clarify and that he is reviewing these practices so that no one feels cheated."
But the controversy between Americans and Europeans continued to swell this week with new revelations in the press.
According to the Washington Post, the NSA was intercepting the data of hundreds of millions of Google and Yahoo users.
The newspaper, which cites documents obtained from former NSA consultant Edward Snowden, claims that the program called "MUSCULAR", and conducted with the British counterpart of the NSA, GCHQ, allows these two agencies to recover data from the optical fibers used by the Internet giants.
According to one of the documents, some 181 million items were collected in January alone - ranging from metadata on emails, to text elements or audio or video documents.
These interceptions would take place outside the United States.
But Yahoo and Google have denied any connection to these practices.
For ten days, several major newspapers in France, Germany, Spain and Italy, have revealed that the NSA would have massively intercepted data and communications from allies of the United States and its leaders, including German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Faced with the anger of European states and while leaks in the American press claimed that the American president was not aware of such wiretapping, Barack Obama refused to speak on this subject, citing national security.
On the other hand, the head of the powerful NSA, General Keith Alexander, denied that his intelligence agency had captured tens of millions of communications from European citizens.
He even passed the buck to the European intelligence services that would have seized these communications, before providing them to the NSA.
This would concern "military operations" in countries where these NATO allies cooperate with the United States and it would not target Europe at all, said General Alexander.
And the controversy spread Friday to Asia.
Indonesia has summoned Australia's ambassador, whose mission is accused of being used by the Americans as part of a vast international espionage network that has also drawn the ire of China.
Early puberty: Aging earlier
Studies show that African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than white girls.
Physical changes don't mean puberty is imminent
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
Experts believe obesity epidemic could be a trigger for early puberty
The trend towards precocious puberty is not as pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in family and child health issues.
Should a mother worry if her daughter's breasts and pubic hair start growing at age 7 or 8?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics held this week in Orlando, Florida, Dr. Paul Kaplowitz, a child endocrinologist, explained that these early physical changes are quite common among young American women and represent a new normal.
"I spend a lot of time reassuring parents ‚Äî in general, it doesn't indicate a rapid progression to full puberty," Kaplowitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as budding breasts, hair under the arms and in the pubic area, and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a slight advance in the age of first menstruation over the past four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12 and a half years, up from 12 three-quarters in 1970.
"Once the chest starts to grow, it takes at least two or three years before the first period appears," said Kaplowitz, also the author of "Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem."
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty will evolve.
There is some debate about what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but it is considered "early" when breast development is accompanied by sudden growth before the age of 8.
In most cases, development slows down or stops ‚Äì this is something a pediatrician can monitor closely.
A faster progression may justify tests performed by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatments to delay the onset of the first period and prevent other consequences: premature aging of the bones that can slow growth and small stature in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug and hormonal treatment are based on the child's age, developmental rate, growth rate and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious with medication but acknowledges that "controlling puberty can alleviate some behavioral problems and the feeling for young girls to be different from others."
The other big problem is understandable: Parents simply don't want their very young daughters to menstruate.
"They fear the risk of pregnancy or even how they're going to handle hygiene issues," Kaplowitz said.
"It was a shock," recalls a woman whose daughter had her first period at age 10.
Even though there were signs and we had talked about menstruation, she was not emotionally prepared.
She came home from school scared and upset to be the first among her friends.
There are many theories brought to the public attention about the causes of precocious puberty.
Yet there is no consistent theory that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are responsible.
Both boys, like girls, reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz argues that the most credible hypothesis is that of the obesity epidemic.
He participated in a study conducted on girls aged 6 to 9 years that links the percentage of fat mass to the onset of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other influential factors.
In this country, young African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than young white girls.
There are various explanations.
Globally, the mechanisms of precocious puberty seem to be influenced by everything from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another problem: Although boys have hair on their faces and pubic areas at younger ages, the trend toward true precocious puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other physicians attending the AAP conference emphasized the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common, even in infants and toddlers.
"We need to be careful about how we identify the true onset of puberty," said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a child endocrinologist working at Goryeb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to ask their pediatrician for advice on how to talk with their child.
"It may mean having a conversation earlier than expected," Kaplowitz explained.
If you stay calm, your child will generally respond well.
Girls with precocious puberty need to be reassured that even when it happens earlier than expected, the process is part of life.
