How was your arrival on French soil?
We land at Orly.
Chirac, Prime Minister, is there.
It's a bit brutal.
There is an incredible stampede.
And a lot of media.
When I left there were three TV channels.
I come back and there are plenty.
The descent of the stairs of the plane, the reunion with my son and my parents, my friends, all this is extremely emotional.
Between the airport and my home, many motorcycles follow our car that Roussin drives.
The bikers shoot each other to take pictures and follow me to my house where I have to do a little police to prevent some from getting in.
The media pressure is enormous.
It doesn't stop, we are in a good position to know...
But the state of emotion and fatigue is such that it is difficult to see clearly.
We come out of a hole and we are suddenly in the media spotlight.
It's a bit complicated, a little violent, quite complex to manage.
But we did the hardest.
The same evening, I'm at 8pm, the next day I'm also on TV.
Then begins a kind of rehabilitation to life, very slowly, for one or two months that are a bit like a vacation.
How were the medical examinations and the DGSE debriefing?
I had a first medical check in Corsica.
The rest was done in Val-de-Gr√¢ce the days following my return: X-rays, examinations of all kinds and meeting with a psychiatrist.
It is not a session that does everything but we know that we can count on him, remind him if necessary, that we are not left to ourselves.
That is part of the process.
I also met with the intelligence services.
They asked me about the hostage-takers.
It made sense.
It didn't bother me.
How do you react today to the release of the four hostages from Niger?
I listen to what is being said.
The debate on ransoms in particular.
Some things annoy me, others less so.
I try to distinguish between questions about my past as a hostage and my hat as president of the association "Hostages of the world" which allows me to put distance, and seems to me much more interesting to address.
For example, I wonder about the definition of resilience.
Above all, I am fighting, with others, for the recognition of the legal status of the hostage.
I think there is a problem of semantics.
Hostage-taking must be described as "political" hostage-taking - which is most of the time - and hostage-taking must be allowed access to justice, complaints and the taking of hostages to the International Criminal Court.
Today, once again, everyone is in compassion, in emotion, and rejoices at the release of these hostages.
But who says that perhaps these hostages could also have access to justice?
A tribunal in The Hague is made for that.
Why should we not tell the hostage-takers "you have flouted the rules of war, like those of all the Geneva Conventions, we will bring you to justice"?
Yet it seems to me to be well-founded, legitimate, and common sense.
This message is heard, but not listened to, and it shocks me.
This is my main fight.
