George Kerevan: The break-up of Europe gives the Scots a choice
Another day, another disturbing story of independence.
This time, we are warned that an independent Scotland would be required to join the European free movement area in order to join the EU.
And now we hear stories of passport control in Berwick and a barbed wire border along Hadrian's Wall.
While it is true that the Strathclyde newspaper pointed to the potential economic benefits of greater freedom of movement with the rest of Europe, this was not in the headlines (and was to be expected).
Nor has anyone said that EU member states spend much of their time circumventing their formal rules when it suits them.
Since Scotland is not part of the Schengen area at the moment, continued non-compliance with the rules would be a small concession that Brussels could offer in return for everything it wants from the Scots.
So this is a story that is not a story.
And a story so old that it's now frozen: I first heard the gossip that "independence means passport control" more than 40 years ago.
However, we have forgotten an interesting point in this interpretation of an old dusty tale.
Why should an independent Scotland follow Europe's instructions, in fact?
Why exchange the yoke of London for that of Brussels, especially now?
Here is the real news about Europe: the great post-war plan to unify Europe is definitely at a standstill.
With the euro crisis, Project Europe is officially dead.
Across Europe, parties opposing the EU or pushing for the abandonment of the euro as a common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party, founded only this year and came out of nowhere, garnered almost five million votes in September's federal elections and took the Liberal Democratic Party (equivalent to our Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been national opposition to the project of creating a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has marked a turning point.
The austerity imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, coupled with the straitjacket weighing on national economies through membership of the single currency, has led many to believe that Project Europe has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments running excessive budget deficits ‚Äì this was only true for Greece.
Instead, the European system has imposed on its members exchange rates favourable to German exporters ‚Äì something German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of a devaluation of the national currency, the countries of southern Europe are left with an intrinsic productivity problem vis-√†-vis Germany.
The only recourse is to make deep cuts in wages and public spending ‚Äì encouraged by Berlin.
Beyond the current fiscal and monetary problems, there is a deeper productivity malaise in Europe.
As a result of the "green" energy policies imposed by Brussels ‚Äì which are a reason to subsidize French and German energy companies at the expense of the consumer ‚Äì European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas as the United States.
This is a crippling disadvantage in terms of costs, as we have already seen at Grangemouth.
All wage freezes in the world will not prevent the European petrochemical industry from being penalised by cheap US shale gas.
As a result, the revolt is brewing, especially in France, one of the great leaders of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a passport to its political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policy in Europe, leaving the ailing French economy to struggle.
As a result, Marine Le Pen's far-right party, the anti-European National Front, has just won a crucial by-election, returning the Socialists to power in third place.
The National Front is now the most popular party in France with 24% of the vote ‚Äì a timely warning to Britain's Labour Party that it cannot assume that a split in the right will automatically favour the left.
What is Marine Le Pen doing with her newfound popularity with the white French working class?
She wants to use next year's European elections to create an anti-single-currency, anti-European bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-European parties do well in these elections, which is very possible, such a bloc could control the European Parliament for the first time.
This is what I think: very soon, anti-European and anti-single currency sentiment in Europe will unify and eventually kill the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will return to something more like the free "Europe of (sovereign) nations" favored by General de Gaulle.
Germany and some of its satellite economies may retain the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect the U.K. to distance itself from this project, and I hope it will make the U.S. look soft.
However, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left behind in the Atlantic.
And Scotland, in all this?
We can decide to be a region of Little England (essentially).
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which includes sending Berlin and Brussels for a walk.
I believe that Scotland could live with a freer European agreement provided that we kept our own currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries would be easier in a non-federal Europe of Nations.
Otherwise, we should emulate Norway and retain our economic independence.
Scotland's SNP government is ‚Äì and noteworthy ‚Äì the most successful anti-austerity political movement in Europe, winning a spectacular majority in 2011 based on its opposition to cuts proposed (and implemented) by Labour Chancellor of the Exchequer Alistair Darling and the Conservative/Liberal Democrat coalition that followed.
It would be ridiculous now for Scotland to vote for independence if it is to accept the austerity imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
