Back in black and white for Marie Chouinard, who presents at Danse Danse her two new group choreographies: the first inspired by the inks and poems of Henri Michaux, the second inspired by the famous piano solos Gymnop√©dies by Satie.
An evening that allows you to see the whole prism of Chouinard, from art to tics and from ink black to white.
A white screen serves as the back wall.
On the carpet, also white, in the immense space that is the Th√©√¢tre Maisonneuve, a body walks forward, thin as a line and dressed in black.
On the screen, an ink by Henri Michaux is projected.
The body, simple stroke, takes its shape.
And this form will be that of the whole piece: a row of physical imitations of the drawings.
The dancers, dressed entirely in black, only hands and faces uncovered, wait on either side of the playing area, rush when the next spelling appears, embody it, come out running.
This black and white playing by Henri Michaux is done in relays of solos, in groups in unison (a mass that makes solo), in large groups of twelve solos where each performs his sign.
One thinks of "Gloire du matin", where, solo, Chouinard performed a series of choreographic tasks written on cartels, placed in line at the front of the stage.
It's the same principle, giant PowerPoint version.
Here the music is loud, percussion and electric guitars.
The energy is high, the pace always fast.
There will be a break when Carol Prieur takes refuge under the dance mat, to deliver, microphone in hand, without sobriety or restraint, a part of Michaux's poem, monotonous and monotonous in the auction, and continues by dancing.
And the music to leave, and the sequence to resume.
This loud and energetic discharge, long, if possible, ends up deafening and numbing.
As does the regularity of the visual rhythm.
There are some beautiful flashes - image creation has always been a strength at Chouinard - such as those hair that ruffle or those black fabrics that lengthen the lines.
But the choreographic approach lacks composition.
One has the impression that the choreographer, instead of going to meet Michaux's work, has imposed herself, with her tics.
Result: the bodies seem flat in front of the drawings.
Michaux's inks, like Gestalt forms, open a wider imagination and game than dance, which is more porous.
Only the ending, in negative, with its dancers chopped by a strobe light and white signs in a suddenly black theater, touches magic.
The audience liked it, the welcome was warm.
The Gymnop√©dies, after the intermission, is richer.
The stage is partly draped in grey, the dancers and a piano are covered with fabrics, like furniture in a neglected house.
At the piano, dancers take turns playing the scores.
Their clumsiness in music, touching, gives a real fragility.
On stage, couples pass in love duets, very sensual, even erotic.
Group work, small transition solos, moving ensembles, choirs, the writing is less binary.
Buffoons appear, also familiar to Chouinard, sporting red noses, in highly polarized male-female courtships.
Loves are carnivorous, elusive or playful.
The gestures, the laughter and the little cries beautifully transpose the archaic, the grace and the ridicule of the bodies in coitus, of the beings that merge.
But the play really takes off after the salute.
A clown returns to the scene when the audience leaves.
There, everything becomes permissible: the fourth wall falls, the universes explored are superimposed, the dancers cabotinate, descend among the spectators, grumble, smoke, short-circuit, play the codes of applause, stretch the sauce in a cleverly calculated disorder that remains sensual.
Joy and madness transpire, and it is Chouinard's art to contaminate the public.
