Beijing blames Uighur group for Tiananmen attack
China's internal security chief on Friday accused a group of Uighur separatists in Xinjiang of being behind the car bomb attack that killed five people in Tiananmen Square in central Beijing on Monday.
The vehicle, an SUV, plowed into the crowd in the Chinese capital's famous square, a symbol of the deadly crackdown in 1989, and caught fire, killing its three passengers and two bystanders.
Meng Jianzhu, a member of the Political Bureau in charge of internal security issues, accused the East Turkestan Islamic Movement of being the instigator of the attack.
Many Uighurs, a Turkic-speaking minority living in Xinjiang, call this Chinese province East Turkestan.
For the Chinese government, this movement is responsible for the frequent eruptions of violence that occur there animated by demands for independence.
"The violent terrorist incident that occurred in Beijing was organized and premeditated," Meng told Hong Kong's Phoenix TV.
"The group that was standing behind the scenes was the East Turkestan Islamic Movement," he added, with Xinhua news agency quoted him as saying.
Chinese police identified the driver of the vehicle whose name suggests he is of Uighur origin and said his wife and mother were with him in the car.
The latter also contained containers filled with gasoline and a flag with Orthodox religious inscriptions.
The incident left 42 people injured.
The East Turkestan Islamic Movement is considered a terrorist organization by the United States and the United Nations.
